Intro

This is a super fast way to look up hexcode colors in R. Normally youâd have to head to a page like this and squint until you find a color code that works. But thereâs another way thanks to the {Scales} package.

Use show_col and col2hcl

If you know the color already.

show_col(col2hcl("royalblue"))

More than one color

Hue

If you want to vary the color slightly use the Hue argument.

Click to find out the definition of âHueâ ð

Hue literally mean color ð

#ð

tomatoes <- rep("tomato", 6) # we have to create a vector here to allow multiple to show
show_col(col2hcl(tomatoes, h = seq( 0, 25, length = 6)))

Lets break this down.

show_col allows the visualization to occur in R

col2hcl is the function that gives us the hex codes

  • within this argument we throw in our vector (i.e, our ð)
  • Then we can modify our hue a bit wtih seq and any number between [0, 360]
  • Keep the 0 in the beginning, and if you want a lot of similar colors keep the next number (or the range between the two) small.

length this just lets R know how many color we want to show.

Chroma

If you want the intensity to change we can use the chroma argument.

We use the identical process as before this time we use âcâ. The range for chroma is [0, 100]

Note

We already created an our tomatoes object so we donât have to redefine it.

show_col(col2hcl(tomatoes, c = seq( 0, 25, length = 6)))

Let max the argument out and see what happens

show_col(col2hcl(tomatoes, c = seq( 0, 100, length = 6)))

Luminance

If we want to look at variations in the intensity of light of our ðs we can use the l argument.

Our luminescence range is [0, 100]

show_col(col2hcl(tomatoes, l = seq( 0, 100, length = 6)))

Hope that helps!
